    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-10-24T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-10-24T00:00:00-05:00" n="346"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d346">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 300.115/28385</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Commercial Adviser of the British Embassy</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_CSRF1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Crawford</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the Foreign Trade Adviser of the Department of
                        State</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_FWB1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Fleming</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-10-24">
                            <hi rend="italic">October 24, 1915</hi>.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Dear Mr.</hi>
                    <persName corresp="#p_FWB1">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Fleming</hi>
                    </persName>: With reference to your letter of the 23d instant regarding the
                    voucher or guarantee that would be required, by the British Government on
                    applications from universities, colleges, and public bodies for permits to bring
                    forward scientific or educational works in German, I am to inform you that no
                    more would he required than that every such application should have an
                    endorsement by the official authority appointed that he is satisfied that the
                    application is genuine, that the volumes for which application is made are in
                    fact intended for the use of that institution.</p>
                <p>I should be glad if you would be so kind as to let me know in due course whether
                    the Librarian of Congress would be willing to undertake this service.</p>
                <p>Yours very truly,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_CSRF1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">R. F. Crawford</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
